SIMPLE: light
RECORDS: 8

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Light
<hw>Light</hw> <pr>(l⟦imac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>light</ets>, <ets>liht</ets>, AS. <ets>le⟦iacute⟧ht</ets>; akin to
OS. <ets>lioht</ets>, D. & G. <ets>licht</ets>, OHG. <ets>lioht</ets>,
Goth. <ets>liuha⟦thorn⟧</ets>, Icel. <ets>lj⟦omac⟧s</ets>, L.
<ets>lux</ets> light, <ets>lucere</ets> to shine, Gr. <grk>leyko`s</grk>
white, Skr. <ets>ruc</ets> to shine. ⟦root⟧122. Cf. <er>Lucid</er>,
<er>Lunar</er>, <er>Luminous</er>, <er>Lynx</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>That agent, force, or action in nature by the operation of which
upon the organs of sight, objects are rendered visible or
luminous.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Light</xex> was regarded formerly as consisting of
material particles, or corpuscules, sent off in all directions from
luminous bodies, and traversing space, in right lines, with the known
velocity of about 186,300 miles per second; but it is now generally
understood to consist, not in any actual transmission of particles or
substance, but in the propagation of vibrations or undulations in a
subtile, elastic medium, or ether, assumed to pervade all space, and to
be thus set in vibratory motion by the action of luminous bodies, as the
atmosphere is by sonorous bodies. This view of the nature of light is
known as the <xex>undulatory or wave theory</xex>; the other, advocated
by Newton (but long since abandoned), as the <xex>corpuscular</xex>,
<xex>emission</xex>, or <xex>Newtonian theory</xex>. A more recent
theory makes light to consist in electrical oscillations, and is known
as the <xex>electro-magnetic theory</xex> of light.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which furnishes, or is a source of, light, as
the sun, a star, a candle, a lighthouse, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then he called for a <qex>light</qex>, and sprang in.</q>
<rj><qau>Acts xvi. 29.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And God made two great <qex>lights</qex>; the greater
<qex>light</qex> to rule the day, and the lesser <qex>light</qex> to
rule the night.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. i. 16.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The time during which the light of the sun is
visible; day; especially, the dawn of day.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The murderer, rising with the <qex>light</qex>, killeth the poor
and needy.</q> <rj><qau>Job xxiv. 14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The brightness of the eye or eyes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He seemed to find his way without his eyes;⟦br⟧
For out o'door he went without their helps,⟦br⟧
And, to the last, bended their <qex>light</qex> on me.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The medium through which light is admitted, as a
window, or window pane; a skylight; in architecture, one of the
compartments of a window made by a mullion or mullions.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There were windows in three rows, and <qex>light</qex> was against
<qex>light</qex> in three ranks.</q> <rj><qau>I Kings
vii.4.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Life; existence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O, spring to <qex>light</qex>, auspicious Babe, be born !</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Open view; a visible state or condition; public
observation; publicity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The duke yet would have dark deeds darkly answered; he would never
bring them to <qex>light</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>The power of perception by vision.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My strength faileth me; as for the <qex>light</qex> of my eyes, it
also is gone from me.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. xxxviii. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>That which illumines or makes clear to the mind;
mental or spiritual illumination; enlightenment; knowledge;
information.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He shall never know⟦br⟧
That I had any <qex>light</qex> of this from thee.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>Prosperity; happiness; joy; felicity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then shall thy <qex>light</qex> break forth as the morning, and
thy health shall spring forth speedily.</q> <rj><qau>Is. lviii.
8.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <fld>(Paint.)</fld> <def>The manner in which the light
strikes upon a picture; that part of a picture which represents those
objects upon which the light is supposed to fall; the more illuminated
part of a landscape or other scene; -- opposed to <ant>shade</ant>. Cf.
<er>Chiaroscuro</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>Appearance due to the particular facts and
circumstances presented to view; point of view; <as>as, to state things
fairly and put them in the right <ex>light</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Frequent consideration of a thing . . . shows it in its several
<qex>lights</qex> and various ways of appearance.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <def>One who is conspicuous or noteworthy; a model or
example; <as>as, the <ex>lights</ex> of the age or of
antiquity</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Joan of Arc,⟦br⟧
A <qex>light</qex> of ancient France.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>14.</sn> <fld>(Pyrotech.)</fld> <def>A firework made by filling a
case with a substance which burns brilliantly with a white or colored
flame; <as>as, a Bengal <ex>light</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Light</xex> is used figuratively to denote that
which resembles physical light in any respect, as illuminating,
benefiting, enlightening, or enlivening mankind.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><mcol><col><b>Ancient lights</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>,
<col><b>Calcium light</b></col>, <col><b>Flash light</b></col>,
etc.</mcol> <cd>See under <er>Ancient</er>, <er>Calcium</er>, etc.</cd>
-- <col><b>Light ball</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>a ball of
combustible materials, used to afford light; -- sometimes made so as to
be fired from a cannon or mortar, or to be carried up by a rocket.</cd>
-- <col><b>Light barrel</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>an empty power
barrel pierced with holes and filled with shavings soaked in pitch, used
to light up a ditch or a breach.</cd> -- <col><b>Light dues</b></col>
<fld>(Com.)</fld>, <cd>tolls levied on ships navigating certain waters,
for the maintenance of lighthouses.</cd> -- <col><b>Light
iron</b></col>, <cd>a candlestick.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> --
<col><b>Light keeper</b></col>, <cd>a person appointed to take care of a
lighthouse or light-ship.</cd> -- <col><b>Light money</b></col>,
<cd>charges laid by government on shipping entering a port, for the
maintenance of lighthouses and light-ships.</cd> -- <col><b>The light of
the countenance</b></col>, <cd>favor; kindness; smiles.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lord, lift thou up <qex>the light of thy countenance</qex> upon
us.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. iv. 6.</qau></rj></p>

<p>-- <col><b>Northern lights</b></col>. <cd>See <cref>Aurora
borealis</cref>, under <er>Aurora</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To bring to
light</b></col>, <cd>to cause to be disclosed.</cd> -- <col><b>To come
to light</b></col>, <cd>to be disclosed.</cd> -- <col><b>To see the
light</b></col>, <cd>to come into the light; hence, to come into the
world or into public notice; <as>as, his book never <ex>saw the
light</ex></as>.</cd><-- also, see the light of day; (b) to come to
understand (sometimes used ironically, said of a person who professes to
change his opinion after he has been convinced that it will be in his
own interest if the facts are different from his initial beliefs) --> --
<col><b>To stand in one's own light</b></col>, <cd>to take a position
which is injurious to one's own interest.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>Light</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Light
<hw>Light</hw> <pr>(l⟦imac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>le⟦iacute⟧ht</ets>. See <er>Light</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar</pos>. <adjf>Lighter</adjf>
<pr>(l⟦imac⟧t"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>; <pos>superl</pos>.
<adjf>Lightest</adjf>.]</amorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having light; not dark
or obscure; bright; clear; <as>as, the apartment is
<ex>light</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>White or whitish; not intense or very marked; not of
a deep shade; moderately colored; <as>as, a <ex>light</ex> color; a
<ex>light</ex> brown; a <ex>light</ex> complexion.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Light</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Light
<hw>Light</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Lighted</conjf> <pr>(l⟦imac⟧t"⟦ecr⟧d)</pr> or <conjf>Lit</conjf>
<pr>(l⟦icr⟧t)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Lighting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>l⟦ymac⟧htan</ets>,
<ets>l⟦imac⟧htan</ets>, to shine. ⟦root⟧122. See <er>Light</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To set fire to; to cause to burn;
to set burning; to ignite; to kindle; <as>as, to <ex>light</ex> a candle
or lamp; to <ex>light</ex> the gas</as>; -- sometimes with
<ptcl>up</ptcl>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If a thousand candles be all <qex>lighted</qex> from one.</q>
<rj><qau>Hakewill.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And the largest lamp is <qex>lit</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Absence might cure it, or a second mistress⟦br⟧
<qex>Light</qex> up another flame, and put out this.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To give light to; to illuminate; to fill with light;
to spread over with light; -- often with <xex>up</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ah, hopeless, lasting flames! like those that burn⟦br⟧
To <qex>light</qex> the dead.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One hundred years ago, to have <qex>lit</qex> this theater as
brilliantly as it is now <qex>lighted</qex> would have cost, I suppose,
fifty pounds.</q> <rj><qau>F. Harrison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sun has set, and Vesper, to supply⟦br⟧
His absent beams, has <qex>lighted</qex> up the sky.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To attend or conduct with a light; to show the way
to by means of a light.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His bishops lead him forth, and <qex>light</qex> him on.</q>
<rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To light a fire</b></col>, <cd>to kindle the material of
a fire.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Light</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Light
<hw>Light</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To become ignited; to
take fire; <as>as, the match will not <ex>light</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be illuminated; to receive light; to brighten; --
with <xex>up</xex>; <as>as, the room <ex>light</ex> up very
well</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Light</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Light
<hw>Light</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Lighter</adjf> <pr>(l⟦imac⟧t"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Lightest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>light</ets>,
<ets>liht</ets>, AS. <ets>l⟦imac⟧ht</ets>, <ets>le⟦iacute⟧ht</ets>; akin
to D. <ets>ligt</ets>, G. <ets>leicht</ets>, OHG. <ets>l⟦imac⟧hti</ets>,
Icel. <ets>l⟦emac⟧ttr</ets>, Dan. <ets>let</ets>, Sw.
<ets>l⟦aum⟧tt</ets>, Goth. <ets>leihts</ets>, and perh. to L.
<ets>levis</ets> (cf. <er>Levity</er>), Gr. <grk>'elachy`s</grk> small,
Skr. <ets>laghu</ets> light. ⟦root⟧125.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having
little, or comparatively little, weight; not tending to be the center of
gravity with force; not heavy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These weights did not exert their natural gravity, . . . insomuch
that I could not guess which was <qex>light</qex> or heavy whilst I held
them in my hand.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Not burdensome; easy to be lifted, borne, or carried
by physical strength; <as>as, a <ex>light</ex> burden, or
load</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye shall find rest unto your souls. For my yoke is easy, and my
burden is <qex>light</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. xi. 29,
30.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Easy to be endured or performed; not severe; not
difficult; <as>as, a <ex>light</ex> affliction or task</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Light</qex> sufferings give us leisure to complain.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Easy to be digested; not oppressive to the stomach;
<as>as, <ex>light</ex> food</as>; also, containing little
nutriment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Not heavily armed; armed with light weapons; <as>as,
<ex>light</ex> troops; a troop of <ex>light</ex> horse.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Not encumbered; unembarrassed; clear of impediments;
hence, active; nimble; swift.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Unmarried men are best friends, best masters . . . but not always
best subjects, for they are <qex>light</qex> to run away.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Not heavily burdened; not deeply laden; not
sufficiently ballasted; <as>as, the ship returned
<ex>light</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Slight; not important; <as>as, a <ex>light</ex>
error</as>.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>Well leavened; not heavy; <as>as, <ex>light</ex>
bread</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>Not copious or heavy; not dense; not
inconsiderable; <as>as, a <ex>light</ex> rain; a <ex>light</ex> snow;
<ex>light</ex> vapors.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>Not strong or violent; moderate; <as>as, a
<ex>light</ex> wind</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>Not pressing heavily or hard upon; hence, having an
easy, graceful manner; delicate; <as>as, a <ex>light</ex> touch; a
<ex>light</ex> style of execution.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <def>Easy to admit influence; inconsiderate; easily
influenced by trifling considerations; unsteady; unsettled; volatile;
<as>as, a <ex>light</ex>, vain person; a <ex>light</ex>
mind.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is no greater argument of a <qex>light</qex> and
inconsiderate person than profanely to scoff at religion.</q>
<rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>14.</sn> <def>Indulging in, or inclined to, levity; wanting
dignity or solemnity; trifling; gay; frivolous; airy;
unsubstantial.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Seneca can not be too heavy, nor Plautus too <qex>light</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Specimens of New England humor laboriously <qex>light</qex> and
lamentably mirthful.</q> <rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>15.</sn> <def>Not quite sound or normal; somewhat impaired or
deranged; dizzy; giddy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Are his wits safe? Is he not <qex>light</qex> of brain ?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>16.</sn> <def>Easily bestowed; inconsiderately
rendered.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To a fair semblance doth <qex>light</qex> faith annex.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>17.</sn> <def>Wanton; unchaste; <as>as, a woman of <ex>light</ex>
character</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>light</qex> wife doth make a heavy husband.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>18.</sn> <def>Not of the legal, standard, or usual weight;
clipped; diminished; <as>as, <ex>light</ex> coin</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>19.</sn> <def>Loose; sandy; easily pulverized; <as>as, a
<ex>light</ex> soil</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Light cavalry</b></col>, <col><b>Light
horse</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>light-armed soldiers
mounted on strong and active horses.</cd> -- <col><b>Light
eater</b></col>, <cd>one who eats but little.</cd> -- <col><b>Light
infantry</b></col>, <cd>infantry soldiers selected and trained for rapid
evolutions.</cd> -- <col><b>Light of foot</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>Having a light step.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>Fleet.</cd> --
<col><b>Light of heart</b></col>, <cd>gay, cheerful.</cd> --
<col><b>Light oil</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>the oily product,
lighter than water, forming the chief part of the first distillate of
coal tar, and consisting largely of benzene and toluene.</cd> --
<col><b>Light sails</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>all the sails
above the topsails, with, also, the studding sails and flying jib.</cd>
<au>Dana.</au> -- <col><b>Light sleeper</b></col>, <cd>one easily
wakened.</cd> -- <col><b>Light weight</b></col>, <cd>a prize fighter,
boxer, wrestler, or jockey, who is below a standard medium weight. Cf.
<cref>Feather weight</cref>, under <er>Feather</er>.</cd>
<mark>[Cant]</mark> -- <col><b>To make light of</b></col>, <cd>to treat
as of little consequence; to slight; to disregard.</cd> -- <col><b>To
set light by</b></col>, <cd>to undervalue; to slight; to treat as of no
importance; to despise.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 852 pr=VMG --></p>

<p><ent>Light</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Light
<hw>Light</hw> <pr>(l⟦imac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Lightly;
cheaply.</def> <rj><au>Hooker.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Light</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 7 ====
HEADWORD: Light
<hw>Light</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Light</er> not heavy, and
cf. <er>Light</er> to alight, and <er>Lighten</er> to make less
heavy.]</ety> <def>To lighten; to ease of a burden; to take off.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From his head the heavy burgonet did <qex>light</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Light</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 8 ====
HEADWORD: Light
<hw>Light</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Lighted</conjf> <pr>(l⟦imac⟧t"⟦ecr⟧d)</pr> <it>or</it>
<conjf>Lit</conjf> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧t)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Lighting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>l⟦imac⟧htan</ets> to
alight orig., to relieve (a horse) of the rider's burden, to make less
heavy, fr. <ets>l⟦imac⟧ht</ets> light. See <er>Light</er> not heavy, and
cf. <er>Alight</er>, <er>Lighten</er> to make light.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To dismount; to descend, as from a horse or carriage; to alight; --
with <ptcl>from</ptcl>, <ptcl>off</ptcl>, <ptcl>on</ptcl>,
<ptcl>upon</ptcl>, <ptcl>at</ptcl>, <ptcl>in</ptcl>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When she saw Isaac, she <qex>lighted</qex> off the camel.</q>
<rj><qau>Gen. xxiv. 64.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Slowly rode across a withered heath,⟦br⟧
And <qex>lighted</qex> at a ruined inn.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To feel light; to be made happy.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It made all their hearts to <qex>light</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To descend from flight, and rest, perch, or settle,
as a bird or insect.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[The bee] <qex>lights</qex> on that, and this, and tasteth
all.</q> <rj><qau>Sir. J. Davies.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On the tree tops a crested peacock <qex>lit</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To come down suddenly and forcibly; to fall; -- with
<ptcl>on</ptcl> or <ptcl>upon</ptcl>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On me, me only, as the source and spring⟦br⟧
Of all corruption, all the blame <qex>lights</qex> due.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To come by chance; to happen; -- with
<ptcl>on</ptcl> or <ptcl>upon</ptcl>; formerly with
<ptcl>into</ptcl>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The several degrees of vision, which the assistance of glasses
(casually at first <qex>lit</qex> on) has taught us to conceive.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They shall <qex>light</qex> into atheistical company.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And here we <qex>lit</qex> on Aunt Elizabeth,⟦br⟧
And Lilia with the rest.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lightable</ent>⟦br⟧
